       "{'SIMILAR_PATTERN_1': {'TITLE_SUMMARY': 'pride_in_identity',\n",
       "  'VARIABLE_STRING': 'p5_1|IDE,p6|IDE,p5|CUL,p15|GLO,p19_3|FED',\n",
       "  'DESCRIPTION': \"There is a strong and consistent sense of pride in being Mexican across multiple questions. For example, 63.42% (p6|IDE), 59.67% (p5|CUL), 63.58% (p19_3|FED), and 55.67% (p15|GLO) of respondents report feeling 'very proud', with additional respondents expressing some pride. The emotion most associated with Mexico is 'pride' at 38.33% (p5_1|IDE). Very few respondents report little or no pride, and the number who do not identify as Mexican is extremely low. This indicates that national pride is a core component of what it means to be Mexican.\"},\n",
       " 'SIMILAR_PATTERN_2': {'TITLE_SUMMARY': 'positive_values_traits',\n",
       "  'VARIABLE_STRING': 'p1_1a_1|IDE,p2_1a_1|IDE',\n",
       "  'DESCRIPTION': \"Mexicans closely associate their national and individual identity with positive values and characteristics. The most frequently mentioned word associated with 'México' is 'Orgullo' (25.25%), followed by 'Costumbres y tradiciones' and 'Historia y cultura' (p1_1a_1|IDE). With respect to 'Mexicano', 'Trabajador' (hardworking) is most commonly mentioned (13.67%), followed by other positive attributes, while negative associations like 'corrupto' are much less frequent (3.58%) (p2_1a_1|IDE). This demonstrates a self-image grounded in positive values and historical or cultural richness.\"},\n",
       " 'SIMILAR_PATTERN_3': {'TITLE_SUMMARY': 'valuing_traditions_customs',\n",
