       "  'DESCRIPTION': \"Although many identify solely as Mexican (42.00%, p7|IDE), a significant portion see themselves as primarily or equally belonging to another regional or local identity (19.42% collectively for 'más yucateco que mexicano' and 'sólo yucateco'). This shows that being Mexican can coexist with other strong local or regional identities, challenging a monolithic view of national identity.\"},\n",
       " 'DIFFERENT_PATTERN_3': {'TITLE_SUMMARY': 'critical_view_of_system',\n",
       "  'VARIABLE_STRING': 'p16_1|GLO,p16_2|GLO,p16_3|GLO',\n",
       "  'DESCRIPTION': \"Despite high personal pride in being Mexican, pride in the country’s democracy, political influence, and economic achievements is much lower. For example, only 7.17% (p16_1|GLO) are very proud of Mexico's democracy, and high proportions report feeling only a little or no pride at all with regards to political and economic accomplishments. This reveals a distinction between personal/national pride and pride in institutions or governance.\"},\n",
       " 'DIFFERENT_PATTERN_4': {'TITLE_SUMMARY': 'persistence_of_divisions',\n",
       "  'VARIABLE_STRING': 'p32|POB',\n",
       "  'DESCRIPTION': \"While a majority believe all Mexicans are equal, a significant 36.92% (p32|POB) believe that there are Mexicans of 'first and second class', indicating perceived social divisions or inequalities contradicting the ideal of national unity.\"},\n",
       " 'DIFFERENT_PATTERN_5': {'TITLE_SUMMARY': 'ambivalence_change_vs_tradition',\n",
       "  'VARIABLE_STRING': 'p78|IDE',\n",
       "  'DESCRIPTION': 'There is no clear consensus on whether the government should retain the ideas of the Revolution or embrace change: 36% favor tradition, 31.5% prefer change, and 24.08% are ambivalent or selective (p78|IDE). This division signals that Mexicans have varied and sometimes contradictory views on whether maintaining traditional ideas is central to national identity.'}}"
      ]
